<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-186-065 </DOCNO><DOCID>10 542 304</DOCID><JOURNAL>Byte  April 1991 v16 n4 p347(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>A smaller, faster OS/2: OS/2 1.3 is a technical success but amarketing flop.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Hamilton, Douglas A.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The new, relatively compact version 1.3 of IBM's OS/2 operatingsystem may be a technologically superior product to MS-DOS and theWindows 3.0 graphical user interface (GUI), but IBM's poormarketing of the product will not attract many of the 50 millionMS-DOS users to OS/2's capabilities.andP;  OS/2 1.3 offers truemultitasking, faster File Manager functionality, virtual memory,and an improved scripting language, but the included PresentationManager GUI is not as sophisticated or flexible as that in Windows3.0.andP;  Printing capabilities have finally been incorporated.andO;Unfortunately, IBM has done little aggressive marketing of OS/21.3, is selling it for $350 and provides no upgrade path toattract MS-DOS users.andP;  Conversely, Microsoft's advertising and $50upgrade to Windows 3.0 attracted a huge number of computer users.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   International Business Machines Corp. (Marketing)Microsoft Corp. (Marketing).andO;Ticker:    IBM; MSFT.andO;Product:   OS/2 1.3 (Operating system) (Marketing)Microsoft Windows 3.0 (Graphical user interface) (Marketing).andO;Topic:     Promotion of ProductComparisonGoals and ObjectivesMarketing StrategySoftware Design.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>